<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="chp5sec2" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Legendre Symbol</title>

  <p> </p>

  <definition xml:id="definition-legendre_symbol">
    <title>Legendre Symbol</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Given an odd prime <m>p</m> and an integer <m>a</m>, the <term>Legendre symbol</term> <m>\left(\frac{a}{p}\right)</m> is defined as
            <m>
                \legendre{a}{p} = \begin{cases}
                    1 \amp \text{if } a \text{ is a quadratic residue modulo } p \\
                    -1 \amp \text{if } a \text{ is a quadratic non-residue modulo } p\\
                    0 \amp \text{if } a \equiv 0 \pmod{p}
                \end{cases}
            </m>
        </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

<p>
  For reasons we will not discuss here, Python quickly computes the Legendre symbol using the built in function <m>\texttt{kronecker(a,p)}</m>. 
</p>

<sage>
<input>
p = 11
for a in range(p):
  print(a, kronecker(a, p))
</input>
<output>
</output>
</sage>

  <p> 
    We now compute some decomposition results that will enable us to compute complicated Legendre symbols in terms of simpler ones.
  </p>


  <proposition xml:id="proposition-legendre_symbol_properties">
    <title>Properties of the Legendre Symbol</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            If <m>p</m> is an odd prime and <m>a, b \in \Z</m>, then
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>
                      \left(\frac{a}{p}\right) = a^{(p-1)/2} \pmod{p}
                  </m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>
                        \legendre{ab}{p} = \legendre{a}{p}\legendre{b}{p}
                  </m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  If <m>a \equiv b \pmod{p}</m>, then <m>\legendre{a}{p} = \legendre{b}{p}</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  If <m>\gcd(a,p) =  1</m>, then <m>\legendre{a^2b}{p} = \legendre{b}{p}</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
        <p>
            Try a direct proof.  Let the definitions structure your proofs.  You may find  <xref ref="definition-legendre_symbol"/> useful.
        </p>
    </proof>
  </proposition>

  <p> 
    We now compute the Legendre symbol for some special cases. In particular, a few simple values of <m>a</m> as we range across <m>p</m>.
  </p>

   <proposition xml:id="proposition-legendre_symbol_for_one">
    <title>The Legendre Symbol for <m>1</m></title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            If <m>p</m> is an odd prime, then <m>\legendre{1}{p}=1</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
        <p>
            Try a direct proof.  Let the definitions structure your proofs.  You may find  <xref ref="definition-legendre_symbol"/> useful.
        </p>
    </proof>
  </proposition>

   <proposition xml:id="proposition-legendre_symbol_for_neg_one">
    <title>The Legendre Symbol for <m>-1</m></title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            If <m>p</m> is an odd prime, then <m>\legendre{-1}{p} = (-1)^{(p-1)/2}</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
        <p>
            Try a direct proof.  Let the definitions structure your proofs.  You may find  <xref ref="definition-legendre_symbol"/> useful.
        </p>
    </proof>
  </proposition>

     <proposition xml:id="proposition-legendre_symbol_for_two">
    <title>The Legendre Symbol for <m>2</m></title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            If <m>p</m> is an odd prime, then <m>\legendre{2}{p} = (-1)^{(p^2-1)/8}</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
        <p>
            Try a direct proof.  Let the definitions structure your proofs.  You may find  <xref ref="definition-legendre_symbol"/> useful.
        </p>
    </proof>
  </proposition>

<sage>
<input>
a = 1
for p in prime_range(100):
  print(p, kronecker(a, p))
</input>
<output>
</output>
</sage>


</section>